Pc3A has an N-terminal pS-rich block and a C-terminal block of roughly equal size enriched in K and arginine (R) residues (Fig. 3B) [7,19,22]. Quantitative energy-dispersive X-ray spectroscopy of sectioned adhesive glands revealed that phosphorus, and therefore the Pc3A and Pc3B proteins, occur exclusively in the sub-granules of the heterogeneous granules, co-localized with approximately 0.5 Mg2+ ions per phosphate group (Fig. 3 C,D) [23]. Only background levels of Ca were detected in the heterogeneous granules and sub-granules. The pH of the adhesive granules has not been measured and the pKa2 of the phosphate groups is unknown, which makes a precise accounting of charge balance impossible. Nevertheless, if the phosphates are monoanionic, the concentration of Mg2+ ions are sufficient to balance the negative charges on the phosphates. The R-rich cationic block of Pc3A would also contribute to phosphate charge neutralization within the heterogeneous sub-granules. The high concentration of Mg2+ also implies the presence of a Mg2+ ion transporter responsible for concentrating Mg2+ within the heterogeneous granules. The form, fluid or solid, of the condensed polyphosphates in the heterogeneous sub-granules within the adhesive gland has not been determined experimentally. However, synthetic methacrylates copolymers that mimic Pc3B (Fig. 4A) with ~ 70 mol% phosphate side chains (pPEMA70) form clear homogeneous coacervates when mixed with Mg2+ ions at pH 8.4 and temperatures less than 20 °C (Fig. 4B,C) [24]. Coacervation of pPEMA and Mg2+ is not affected by salinity; coacervate volume is constant in NaCl concentrations ranging from 0 to 3.0 M (not shown). A complete description of the simple coacervation of synthetic pPEMA with Mg2+ will be reported elsewhere since the primary topic of this paper is the natural adhesive. The demonstration that Mg2+/ pPEMA forms clear homogeneous fluid coacervates (Fig. 4C) at the temperature and salinity of the ocean provides empirical evidence that it is physicochemically possible that the heterogenous sub-granules of Mg2+ and Pc3A/B are stored as fluid coacervates within the secretory pathway, and are in a fluid state at the time of secretion.
4. Adhesive delivery
The sightless animals depend on the so-called building organ, a dexterous pair of opposed finger-like appendages just below the mouth, for constructing their tubular shells (Fig. 5A). Suspended sandgrains and shell fragments are collected by ciliated tentacles from the water column and transported to the building organ for evaluation. Mineral particles of suitable size (~ 0.5 mm), shape, and surface chemistry are pinched within the building organ “fingers”, carefully positioned onto the end of the tube, and held in place to minimize gaps. Minutes dabs of glue are then applied from the building organ into the narrow gap where particles are in contact. The glue emanates from microscopic pores in the ciliated surface distributed around the entire circumference of the building organ (Fig. 5B,C). The pores frequently occur in close pairs, tempting speculation that one pore is the exit point of a
homogeneous cell and the other pore the exit for a heterogeneous cell. Secretion of the two granule types in close proximity to one another would insure uniform distribution within the glue of the separated adhesive parts, with minimal mixing, during application to the substrate [17,23]. When worms rebuild their tubes in the laboratory with spherical glass beads, the glue is applied only where the beads are in contact and at all contact points (Fig. 6A). The supplemental video (Video S1) reveals how this is accomplished. The worms simultaneously apply two separate aliquots of glue into the two contact sites between three glass beads. The glue is applied from the side of the contact site and wicks into the narrow gap between the beads forming a concave capillary bridge (Fig. 10A). Adhesion of the fluid to the glass surface in seawater is evident from the much less than 90° contact angles of the adhesive with the bead surface. The capillary bridge that forms between the particles provides an immediate attractive normal force between the beads. The capillary force has two components: a Laplace pressure difference across the interface between glue and seawater and the interfacial tension that minimizes the interfacial area [25,26]. From the concave surface of the glue joints, the Laplace pressure is lower in the glue phase than in surrounding aqueous phase, which contributes to the normal attractive force. The fluid bridge, however, would contribute little to the compressive or shear moduli of the joint. When worms were electrically stimulated to secrete adhesive, the granules were intact when they exited through the surface of the building organ (Fig. 6) [15,23]. Soon thereafter the granules rupture and the contents fuse with little mixing into a lumpy crack-penetrating fluid [23]. What triggers rupture of the granules after secretion? To investigate, intact granules isolated from dissected adhesive gland tissue in modified Ringer's buffer (430 mM NaCl,10 mM KCl, 10 mM CaCl2, 50 mM MgCl2, 5 mM Tris, pH 6.5) were surface immobilized in a microscope flow chamber. Solution conditions were then changed to determine if environmental changes caused granule rupture. In seawater, the granules remained intact and their diameter was unchanged. Therefore, differences in pH, ionic strength, or ionic composition between the interior of the adhesive granules and seawater alone do not trigger granule swelling or rupture (Fig. 7A,B). Likewise, the granules did not swell and rupture in low ionic strength distilled water (Fig. 7C,D). However, in the anionic detergent, sodium dodecyl sulfate (SDS), the granules ruptured and internal vacuoles appeared as the granules rapidly swelled into foamy spheres with roughly two-fold greater diameter than the intact granules (Fig. 7E,F). The swelling was limited as though the swelling forces were balanced by a cross-linked network in the adhesive matrix. Hence, each granule appeared to be a pre-organized, preassembled foamy module of the final adhesive that swelled to a fixed extent. This is consistent with the occasional appearance of what appear to be individual granules separated from the main adhesive mass, but which have the porous structure of the bulk adhesive (Fig. 10B, white arrow).
Fig. 4. (A) Structure of poly(phosphoethyl methacrylate (PEMA)-co-hydroxyethyl methacrylate (HEMA). (B) Schematic of Mg2+ induced phase separation (simple coacervation) of pPEMA70. (C) The clear homogeneous liquid coacervate of Mg2+/pPEMA70 is the dense macrophase at the bottom of the bottle.
