Addition of ATP to the flow chamber had a pronounced affect on the granule morphology that was distinct from the effect of SDS. The granules swelled until they ruptured, and appeared to lose their contents as they shrank back to less than the original diameter (Fig. 8A–C). Within 60 s, the granules appeared to be collapsed, empty shells. The granule response was specific to ATP since GTP had no affect on the granules (Fig. 8D–F). The volume and morphological response to ATP suggests there is an ATPase present in the granules membranes. A likely candidate is a vacuolar H+-ATPase, a group of highly conserved and widely distributed transmembrane enzymes that hydrolyze ATP to pump protons across membranes in eukaryotic cells, including secretory vesicle membranes [27]. The transmembrane H+ gradients generated by H+
ATPases, in turn, power transmembrane anti-porters that concentrate components into membrane compartments [28]. The high concentration of Mg2+ ions associated with the Pc3A/B coacervates may be transported across the secretory vesicle membranes and concentrated within the secretory granule power a H+/Mg2+ anti-porter. When a high concentration of ATP was added to isolated granules (Fig. 8A–C), the H+-ATPase may have over-acidified the interior of the granules, thus dissolving the coacervated contents, increasing the osmotic pressure within the granules, causing them to burst and release the dissolved contents. Addition of ATP to isolated granules caused them to rupture, but this is not likely the natural mechanism that ruptures and fuses the granules
Fig. 6. (A) SEM image of the building organ (BO) and mouth. (B) Higher magnification of lower center boxed region showing intact secretory granules. Scale bar = 5 μm. (C) Higher magnification of upper right boxed region. Reproduced from ref. [15].
Fig. 5. (A) SEM images of the building organ. (B) Closer view of ciliated surface. (C) Region indicated by arrow in B. Adhesive exit pores are indicated by white arrow. (D) Higher magnification of paddle-ended cilia. Scale bars: 1 mm, 200, 5, and 20 μm, respectively. Reproduced from ref. [23].
92 R.J. Stewart et al. / Advances in Colloid and Interface Science 239 (2017) 88–96


moments after they are secreted into seawater. Rupture is also not caused by changes in solution conditions, such as pH, upon exposure to seawater (Fig. 7A,B). Instead, the granules may be ruptured mechanically by beating of the dense clusters of unique paddle-ended cilia on the surface of the building organ in immediate proximity to the exit pores (Fig. 5D) [15,23]. The worms also apply a back and forth twisting motion while the adhesive is being injected into the gaps of new particles, which may also contribute to mechanical rupture of the granules [17]. Experimentally, when isolated granules were gently sheared between two glass coverslips in seawater, then examined by SEM, the granules were ruptured, had a foamy appearance, and were fused with other granules while largely maintaining their individual integrity (Fig. 9A,B). In other words, there was little mixing of the granule contents; each granule was a preformed adhesive module fused into the final bulk adhesive. Mechanical rupture of the granules appears to be a plausible mechanism of forming the liquid adhesive immediately after intact granules are secreted. The investigation of bioadhesives in isolated intact granules is a promising experimental approach that allows adhesive proteins and other adhesive components to be studied as packaged with their natural counterparts in their natural form, rather than in isolation. Although the results presented here are preliminary, they demonstrate that adhesive packaging is an energetic cellular process; a transmembrane ATPase controls the environment inside the adhesive packages, such as pH and secondarily ion content. This cellular control is likely critical to concentrating the adhesives into granules and controlling their state of matter, such as in the form of fluid coacervates. Understanding the mechanistic details of adhesive packaging and unpackaging is crucial to understanding the sandcastle worm adhesive system, and any natural adhesive system for that matter.
5. Setting and toughening mechanisms
Capillary forces can provide an immediate attractive normal force, but to efficiently create a bond that bears shear and compressive loads between mineral particles the crack-penetrating liquid adhesive must quickly solidify and harden after application. In a laboratory aquarium,
Fig. 7. (A,C,E) Isolated adhesive granules immobilized on the surface of a flowchamber in modified Ringer's buffer. (B) Granules in A after 60 s in artificial seawater, pH 8.2. (D) Granules in C after 60 s in distilled water. (F) Granules in E after 60 s in 0.05 wt% SDS. The average diameter of the unruptured granules is 2 μm.
Fig. 8. (A–C) Addition of 1 mM ATP to isolated granules in seawater causes granule rupture. (D–F) Addition of 1 mM GTP to isolated granules in seawater has no effect.
R.J. Stewart et al. / Advances in Colloid and Interface Science 239 (2017) 88–96 93


worms gluing sand grains, glass beads, or bone chips to their tubes slightly wiggled the particles as they were held in place with the building organ as adhesive was applied. The particles were consistently released by the building organ in less than 30 s. From these observations, we inferred that the initial solidification, or set, was sufficient in less than 30 s for the particles to be self-supporting in the worm's turbulent environment [17]. The transition of the sandcastle glue from a complex fluid to a porous solid–liquid foam with a surface skin and mostly closed cell architecture is triggered by seawater. This is not as simple as the well-known phase inversion processes used to make porous membranes or filaments whereby polymers or polyelectrolytes in a good solvent are cast or printed into a coagulation bath of poor solvent [29–31]. Looking closely, the closed cells of the glue originate almost entirely from the Mg2+/polyphosphate sub-granules of the heterogeneous adhesive packets (Fig. 10E,F), an observation also reported by Vovelle [14]. The cells are bounded by chemically distinct, well-defined shells and are embedded in a continuous
nanoparticulate, nanoporous matrix [17]. Super-resolution microscopy [32] of resin embedded and thin sectioned glue using fluorescent antipS antibodies revealed that the polyphosphorylated Pc3/B proteins are highly concentrated in the distinct walls of the cells. It appears that during the phase transition to a solid adhesive, the coacervated Mg2+/ polyphosphate in the heterogeneous sub-granules swells and becomes the solid walls of fluid-filled hollow cells [21]. The cells, with an average diameter of 2 μm, are several fold larger in diameter than the subgranules [17]. The disposition of the phospholipids from granule membranes in the final adhesive is unknown. The seawater induced phase transition is driven by a substantial pH differential between the regulated secretory system (pH b6) and the ocean (pH N 8) as well as changes in ionic composition. In the subgranules, the polyphosphates are complexed with Mg2+ only (Fig. 3D), whereas the final adhesive contains both Mg2+ and Ca2+ in a 4:1 M ratio [33]. Both the increase in pH and exchange of Mg2+ with Ca2+ would contribute to insolubilization of the polyphosphates [34]. Granule
