rupture is accompanied by limited swelling, which may be driven by Donnan osmotic pressure that arises from an increase in the internal fixed charge density of the adhesive at the higher pH of seawater. In particular, the phosphates may transition from mono- to dianionic if the internal and external pH differential spans pKa2. Granule swelling may be limited by a cross-linked network in the matrix around the cells. The osmotic pressure would contribute substantially to the compressive and shear moduli of the set glue, and would also pre-stress the walls around the closed cells and the matrix network, further strengthening the joint [35]. During strain, restricted movement of water through the permeable nanoporous matrix may provide a viscous energy dispersive mechanism that further toughens the joint [36]. In other words, the sandcastle glue is an adhesive structure, not simply an adhesive material [17]. The sandcastle glue structure, toughening mechanisms, and the phase inversion mechanisms that give rise to them can be built into synthetic underwater adhesives [37]. As an example, we have recently copied the environmentally triggered coacervate phase transitions of the sandcastle glue to create waterborne in situ setting liquid embolic agents [38]. Such agents are widely used in the clinic for minimally invasive control of blood flow. Applications include treatment of arteriovenous malformations, pre-surgical devascularization of tumors, and traumatic hemorrhage control, to name a few [39,40]. Shear thinning, low viscosity complex coacervates were prepared in hypertonic saline to allow delivery through long, narrow gauge, transarterial catheters. The fluid complex coacervates adhere strongly to blood vessel walls, which allows precise placement of the embolic agent. As they equilibrate toward physiological ionic strength, the embolic coacervates transition into ionic gels as the electrostatic interactions between oppositely charged polyelectrolytes become less shielded by counter ions. The adherent gels occlude the blood vessel and block the flow of blood [38]. The transition from fluid to gel is accompanied by the formation of a discontinuous porous phase (Fig. 11). As described earlier for the fluidfilled multiphasic structure of the natural sandcastle glue (Fig. 10D), the phase inversion mechanism and the resulting porous structure of the in situ setting embolic coacervates may contribute osmotic prestressing and hydraulic toughening mechanisms to the set adhesive. A more complete description of the ionic strength induced phase inversion of the embolic coacervates, their final structure, and material properties will be presented elsewhere.
6. Curing mechanism
The sandcastle glue turns reddish brown, indicative of quinonic cross-linking, over the course of a few hours after secretion [17]. Covalent cross-linking, or curing, of the adhesive provides additional strength to the joint. Covalent curing is catalyzed by a catechol oxidase enzyme that is co-packaged into both the homogeneous and heterogeneous granules [21]. Catechol oxidases are type 3 copper proteins with binuclear Cu active sites that catalyze oxidation of diphenols [41]. The Cu concentration in the sandcastle glue is 0.7 ppm, which is many orders of magnitude higher than the Cu concentration in natural seawater [42]. Therefore, the Cu is most likely present in the adhesive before secretion in the active site of the catechol oxidase. If so, the high Cu content suggests that catechol oxidase is a major protein constituent of the adhesive joints. The ratio of Cu to P is approximately 1:2000, which corresponds to a ratio of catechol oxidase to Pc3A/B on the order of 1:10, estimating that on average Pc3A/B have approximately 100 phosphate groups and catechol oxidase has two copper atoms. The high concentration of enzyme co-packaged within both types of micron-sized packets ensures rapid and homogeneous cross-linking of the modular, multipart adhesive without the need for the enzyme to diffuse through or be mixed into the adhesive. The enzyme remains embedded and active within the glue long after the glue has fully cured [21]. As a major constituent of the glue, the catechol oxidase enzyme is likely also an integral structural element of the glue. We have theorized that complex coacervation may also play a role in the regulation of the catechol oxidase enzyme [18]. The pro-enzyme contains a 74 amino acid pro-peptide, which is unstructured and polyampholytic; 31 of 74 residues are charged at neutral pH. It is possible that the enzyme is electrostatically inactivated before secretion by association of the propeptide with the other polyelectrolytic components in the secretory granules. The highly charged propeptide could also play a role in electrostatically condensing the latent catechol oxidase into the granulated adhesive. Upon granule lysis in seawater, the enzyme may be activated by exchange and rearrangement of electrostatic associations. There are numerous examples of latent plant catechol oxidases that are activated by anionic detergents that bind specific sites of the enzyme [43]. These precedents provide empirical evidence that electrostatic interactions can reversibly switch enzymes on and off.
7. Summary
Sandcastle worms construct reefs under turbulent seawater by joining irregularly shaped particles into external tubular structures. The nature of the process requires a waterborne fluid adhesive, denser than seawater, that will penetrate the narrow spaces between closely opposed particles while not dissolving into the ocean. The fluid adhesive provides an immediate capillary force between the particles, but must rapidly transition into a solid state to resist shear and compressive forces in the turbulent environment. To accomplish this feat, the sandcastle glue is granulated under energetic cellular control into two types of pre-formed, pre-organized adhesive modules. During secretion, the granules rupture and fuse into a crack-penetrating fluid adhesive. Seawater is a poor solvent for the adhesive, which leads to rapid hardening of the coacervate from the outside inward through microphase separation and insolubilization of the adhesive components into a solid–liquid foam. Co-packaged latent catechol oxidase provides a built-in selfinitiated covalent curing mechanism. The undersea glue of the sandcastle worm has inspired the design of wet field medical adhesives [34,37,38, 44–47]. Additional characterization of the environmentally triggered setting mechanisms and multiphasic structure of the sandcastle glue will provide additional insights into the design and manufacture of novel underwater setting nano- and micro-structured adhesives, paints, and membranes.
Fig. 11. Optical section of an adhesive embolic after ionic strength induced phase transition. FITC-labeled protamine sulfate and sodium hexaphosphate at a 1:1 charge ratio forms clear homogeneous complex coacervates in 1200 mM NaCl (pH 7.4). Ten microliters of the clear coacervate was applied to a glass slide submerged in 150 mM NaCl (pH 7.4). The set adhesive was imaged by confocal microscopy after 24 h. Scale bar = 500 μm.
